See the dependencies section in the project.xml.  If the xmlrpc lib is 
available up in the maven1 ibiblio repository, maven should just fetch 
it for you (You may need to add the following to your project.properties 
file because Heritrix is still stuck on maven 1.0.x: 
maven.repo.remote=http://repo1.maven.org/maven).

Here is some more info on Heritrix and lib jars in case the above proves 
insufficent.  Heritrix goes out of its way to defeat mavens dependency 
fetching mechanism.  It does this by setting &#39;maven.jar.override = on&#39; 
in project.properties and then  mapping project.xml dependency 
references to actual locations under the lib directory (again in 
project.properties).  The thinking at the time was that the Heritrix 
checkout contained all needed to run in the likes of eclipse.  Maven was 
not required (This will probably change when we move to m2).

For example, for the libidn jar, in project.xml, it looks like this:

...
        &lt;dependency&gt;
            &lt;id&gt;libidn&lt;/id&gt;
            &lt;version&gt;0.5.9&lt;/version&gt;
            &lt;url&gt;http://www.gnu.org/software/libidn/&lt;/url&gt;
            &lt;properties&gt;
                &lt;war.bundle&gt;true&lt;/war.bundle&gt;
                &lt;ear.bundle&gt;true&lt;/ear.bundle&gt;
                &lt;ear.bundle.dir&gt;APP-INF/lib&lt;/ear.bundle.dir&gt;
                &lt;description&gt;GNU Libidn is an implementation of the 
Stringprep,
                Punycode and IDNA specifications defined by the IETF
                Internationalized Domain Names (IDN) working group, used for
                internationalized domain names.
                &lt;/description&gt;
                &lt;license&gt;GNU Lesser General Public License
                http://www.gnu.org/licenses/lgpl.txt&lt;/license&gt;
            &lt;/properties&gt;
        &lt;/dependency&gt;
...

The &#39;id&#39; libidn from above is then mapped in project properties to the 
libidn-0.5.9.jar with the following project.properties line:

maven.jar.libidn = ${basedir}/lib/libidn-0.5.9.jar

You might also want to edit .classpath so your new jar shows in eclipse.

Hope this helps,
St.Ack


